  "prompt": "What is the difference between O- and O+?",
  "response": "The difference between O- and O+ blood types lies in the presence or absence of the **Rh factor**, also known as the **Rhesus factor**.\n\n*   **O+ (O positive):** This blood type has the Rh factor present on the surface of the red blood cells.\n\n*   **O- (O negative):** This blood type does not have the Rh factor present on the surface of the red blood cells.\n\nIn summary, O+ has the Rh factor, while O- does not. This difference is crucial for blood transfusions, especially in pregnancy, due to the potential for Rh incompatibility.\n",
